filters.title: Service Offering
filters.question: Are you interested in a particular service offering?

options.title: A Test
options.desc: This is a test.

options.title: Advanced Recovery Services
options.desc: In addition to standard Disaster Recovery Services for the recovery of workloads either 'In the Cloud' or 'To the Cloud', the service provider offers a range of add-on services including Business Impact Analysis (BIA) consulting and Workgroup Recovery Services to assist the business BC/DR planning and the resumption of operations in the event of a loss or disaster.

options.title: Advanced Threat Incident Management as a Service
options.desc: Service providers offer a subscription-based service to allow the business to defend against advanced threats by identifying, protecting, and rapidly responding to security incidents. Since this is a subscription-based service, the provider will retain the necessary software licenses and will have the appropriate staff on-hand to assist the customer in handling of incidents.

options.title: Application as a Service
options.desc: Service providers offer access to an application with security controls and persistent data. In some offerings, the software is licensed by seats/month and the customer has no ownership, visibility or control over the underlying licensing or infrastructure. In other offerings, it resembles a managed service, with the customer sometimes retaining software licenses and/or control over the underlying infrastructure.

options.title: Archive as a Service
options.desc: Service Providers offer an archive target to the customer, either on-premise or off-premise. The archive target can be offered as a filesystem or can have application integration, such as a vendor neutral archive for PACS.

options.title: Backup and Recovery as a Service
options.desc: This service is available in many forms, such as Desktop/Laptop backup, ROBO backup, IT backups for hosted workloads, etc. This is typically measured in either "Protected GB/Month" or "Stored GB/Month". Replication of backups to another site is a popular option that is frequently made available to customers.

options.title: Big Data as a Service
options.desc: BI Analytics software delivered as a cloud service. Tools and solutions include big data, business intelligence, predictive analytics, monitoring and application. This includes emerging technologies like Apache Hadoop, Pivotal HD, HAWK, and Gemfire XD.

options.title: Compute as a Service
options.desc: This is usually offered as part of an IaaS offering for x86 workloads. This may also be part of a managed serviced offering for non-x86 workloads. IaaS is often offered in a VM/month increment, with the ability to scale up and down without penalty. Managed Services workloads often only scale up.

options.title: Content Management as a Service
options.desc: Service providers offer a flavor of Application as a Service that's focused on content management. This can sometimes involve on-premise technology that communicates with technology at the Service Provider.

options.title: Data Replication as a Service
options.desc: This service includes a fully managed replication target, and sometimes on premise technology to enable replication from the on premise source to the off premise target. Many times these offerings are technology specific, such as an Isilon replication target, and the customer has some control over the technology utilized.

options.title: Desktop as a Service
options.desc: Remote Desktops provided via the cloud from a service provider using a Software-as-as-Service model. The service provider takes full responsibility for hosting and maintaining the compute, storage and access infrastructure, as well as the virtual software and applications that enable the distribution of a virtual desktop for a fixed monthly fee.

options.title: Disaster Recovery Services
options.desc: Disaster Recovery Services are typically a combination of product and service offerings. Examples could include anything from a fully managed backup replication target to a comprehensive Disaster Recovery offering spanning both technical and operational recovery.

options.title: Enterprise Hybrid Cloud - Co-lo
options.desc: Colocation enables customers to own and manage their Enterprise Hybrid Cloud (EHC) environment completely off-premise, or connect on- and off-premise EHC environments in a secure and isolated hybrid multi-cloud implementation.  Customers configure and operate their own infrastructure within the Service Provider's facilities, which include space, power and cooling.

options.title: Enterprise Hybrid Cloud - Hosting
options.desc: Service Providers deliver an "Enterprise Tenant in Control" service level whereby the Service Provider hosts and manages Enterprise Hybrid Cloud (EHC) physical resources, and customers manage the virtual layer, for example creating and moving virtual machines in cloud environments.

options.title: Enterprise Hybrid Cloud - IaaS
options.desc: Customers can select IaaS offerings through their on-premise Enterprise Hybrid Cloud (EHC) service catalog to provision workloads directly to their Service Provider's cloud. They can also migrate virtual machines and applications between their on-premise EHC and the off-premise cloud through their familiar EHC interface.

options.title: Exchange as a Service
options.desc: This is much like messaging as a service, but is specifically built on MS Exchange. Email, calendar, tasks, etc. are usually included. It is common to charge by the mailbox per month.

options.title: File Sync and Share as a Service
options.desc: This service offering is typically offered in a public cloud model. It includes access to shareable folder structures through a browser, a desktop client and a mobile device application. Optional integration with a customer’s authentication services to ensure secure access.

options.title: Hyperion as a Service
options.desc: This is typically offered as a Private Cloud service or a Managed Service. Hyperion as a Service can include Managed Hosting of a customer's ERP environment.  Sold by the number of users per month.

options.title: Information Security and Compliance as a Service
options.desc: Is an outsourcing model for security and compliance management. Typically, Information Security and Compliance as a Service involves applications such as anti-virus security or software such as RSA delivered over the Internet but the term can also refer to security management provided in-house by an external organization.

options.title: IT Service Management as a Service
options.desc: Refers to the implementation and management of quality IT services that meet the needs of the customer's business. IT Service Management is performed by IT service providers through an appropriate mix of people, process and information technology.

options.title: Managed Availability Services
options.desc: Provides disaster recovery service, business continuity service through a combination of IT consulting and managed services.

options.title: Oracle as a Service
options.desc:
Can be offered in three ways:

1) Virtual Machine Image pre-loaded with an optimized instance of Oracle and launched at a service providers datacenter managed by the customer.

2) Service provider takes responsibility for installing and maintaining the Oracle database, and application owners by according to their usage and access the database over the internet.

3) Managed database hosting, where the database is not offered as a service, but the cloud provider hosts the database and manages it on the application owner’s behalf.

options.title: Platform as a Service
options.desc: Is a category of cloud computing services that provides a computing platform and a solution stack as a service. In this model, the customer creates the software using tools and/or libraries from the provider. The customer also controls software deployment and configuration settings. The provider provides the networks, servers, storage, and other services.

options.title: SAP as a Service
options.desc: This is typically offered as a private cloud service or a managed service. SAP as a Service could be anything from managed hosting of a customer's ERP environment to HANA Cloud Premium.

options.title: SAP HANA as a Service
options.desc: Enable faster innovation with accelerated time to market for mobile “consumer grade” apps, real-time analytics and reporting, and enhanced customer experiences in real time with SAP HANA.

options.title: SharePoint as a Service
options.desc: Microsoft SharePoint is offered as an on-demand software with its associated data that is centrally hosted in the service provider's cloud.  SharePoint is accessed by users via a web browser over the internet.

options.title: Storage as a Service
options.desc: Is an architectural model in which a service provider offers digital storage on their own infrastructure on a subscription basis.  Usually charged on a cost-per-gigabyte-stored and cost-per-data-transfer basis.

options.title: Test Dev as a Service
options.desc: Is Infrastructure-as-a-Service (IaaS) offered exclusively for test and development customer environments. Can either be offered as a physical, virtual or a combination of both to support a test/dev environment. This environment can either be scaled up or down at the customer’s request. Customers deploy their own applications, operating systems and maintain them. Billing is based upon a utility model and the costs usually reflect the amount of resources allocated and consumed.

options.title: Unified Communication as a Service
options.desc: Integrates enterprise messaging, voice, and conferencing to enable easier, more direct collaboration.

options.title: Virtual Data Center as a Service
options.desc: A model in which a service provider provides the entire IT infrastructure over the cloud. VDCaaS engulfs a suite of enterprise-level IT resources bundled together over the Internet to different customers either in a shared or unshared cloud model. A complete VDCaaS solution can contain processing, storage, infrastructure, and application and data center management software. It can also be thought of as the amalgamation of almost all of the different cloud services available and provided as a single solution forming a virtual data center powered by the cloud.
